<header class="header">
  <h1>How Many Growing Degree Days Do Tomatoes Need?</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Tomato maturity depends on heat accumulation.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    In a typical year, tomatoes must mature before frost risk returns at <strong>32°F (0°C)</strong>.
    While seed packets list “days to maturity,” actual ripening depends on accumulated heat — measured as Growing Degree Days (GDD).
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frost Sets the Deadline</h2>

  <p>
    GrowByDate frames frost timing using 1991–2020 climate normals at the <strong>50% probability level</strong>.
    That means there is historically a 50% chance of frost occurring on or before your listed first fall frost date.
  </p>

  <p>
    For tomatoes, that frost date is a hard boundary. Most tomato plants are damaged or killed at 32°F.
    (For temperature thresholds, see
    <a href="/guides/how-cold-is-too-cold-for-tomato-seedlings/">How Cold Is Too Cold for Tomato Seedlings?</a>.)
  </p>

  <p>
    You can identify your typical frost window using the
    <a href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Frost Date Finder</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    The real question becomes:
    <strong>How much heat will accumulate before that frost date arrives?</strong>
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Tomatoes Use Heat to Develop</h2>

  <p>
    Tomatoes are warm-season crops. Development accelerates as temperatures rise and slows when temperatures fall.
  </p>

  <p>
    Most tomato GDD calculations use a base temperature of <strong>50°F (10°C)</strong>.
  </p>

  <pre>
GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </pre>

  <p>
    Each day contributes heat units.
    Over a season, those units accumulate until the plant reaches flowering and fruit maturity.
  </p>

  <p>
    You can estimate how many GDD your location typically accumulates before first frost using the
    <a href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Growing Degree Day Planner</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Typical GDD Ranges for Tomatoes</h2>

  <p>
    Exact GDD requirements vary by variety and growing conditions.
    But broadly, tomato types fall into heat-demand tiers:
  </p>

  <h3>Early / Short-Season Varieties</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Often 1,000–1,200 GDD (base 50)</li>
    <li>Smaller fruit</li>
    <li>Designed for shorter climates</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Mid-Season Varieties</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Approximately 1,200–1,500 GDD</li>
    <li>Standard slicing tomatoes</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Late / Long-Season Varieties</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>1,500–1,800+ GDD</li>
    <li>Large heirlooms and beefsteaks</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine">
    These ranges are approximate and depend on variety genetics and local conditions.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why “Days to Maturity” Can Be Misleading</h2>

  <p>
    A tomato listed as “85 days” assumes relatively warm growing conditions.
  </p>

  <p>
    In cooler climates, development slows because daily GDD totals are lower —
    even if frost-free days are available.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is why calendar-based maturity estimates often underperform in northern climates.
    (See also: <a href="/guides/why-days-to-maturity-isnt-enough-in-cold-climates/">Why Days to Maturity Isn’t Enough in Cold Climates</a>.)
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Example: Two Climates, Same Variety</h2>

  <p>
    Imagine planting a mid-season tomato requiring ~1,400 GDD.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Climate A:</strong> 2,300 GDD before first frost → comfortable margin</li>
    <li><strong>Climate B:</strong> 1,450 GDD before first frost → narrow margin</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In Climate B, a slightly early first frost or a cool summer could prevent full ripening.
  </p>

  <p>
    In Climate A, the same variety is much lower risk.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Risk Tolerance Matters</h2>

  <p>
    Because frost dates are probability-based, some years accumulate more heat than others.
  </p>

  <p>
    If your available GDD barely meets a variety’s estimated requirement,
    you are operating with less buffer in a typical year.
  </p>

  <p>
    If your climate typically accumulates significantly more heat than required,
    your risk of immature fruit before frost is lower.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>How to Plan Tomato Maturity More Reliably</h2>

  <ol>
    <li>Identify your 50% first frost date (32°F definition).</li>
    <li>Estimate total GDD accumulation before that date.</li>
    <li>Choose varieties that fit comfortably within that heat budget.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    If you need additional margin, starting earlier indoors can help —
    provided transplant timing still aligns safely with frost risk.
    You can anchor indoor timing using the
    <a href="/tools/seed-start-planner/">Seed Start Planner</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    For broader frost planning context, see
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How Frost Dates and Growing Degree Days Work Together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Tomatoes typically require 1,000–1,800+ GDD depending on variety.</li>
    <li>Frost at 32°F defines the maturity deadline.</li>
    <li>Heat accumulation—not calendar days—determines ripening speed.</li>
    <li>Short growing seasons require careful variety selection.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    When you evaluate tomatoes using frost timing and Growing Degree Days together,
    maturity planning becomes climate-based rather than calendar-based.
  </p>
</section>